Certainly! You can calculate the sum of the first 12 natural numbers using the formula \( \text{sum} = \frac{n(n+1)}{2} \) in C#. Here is a simple C# program that does this:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int n = 12;
        int sum = n * (n + 1) / 2;

        Console.WriteLine("The sum of the first 12 natural numbers is: " + sum);
    }
}
```

In this code:

- We declare an integer `n` and set it to 12, which represents the first 12 natural numbers.
- We use the formula \( \text{sum} = \frac{n(n+1)}{2} \) to calculate the sum.
- Finally, we print the result to the console.

You can run this program in any C# environment to see the output.
